# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buck-converter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] A **boost converter** or **step-up converter** is a DC-to-DC converter that increases voltage, while decreasing current, from its input (*supply*) to its output (*load*).
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] It is a class of switched-mode power supply (SMPS) containing at least two semiconductors, a diode and a transistor, and at least one energy storage element: a capacitor, inductor, or the two in combination.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] To reduce voltage ripple, filters made of capacitors (sometimes in combination with inductors) are normally added to such a converter's output (load-side filter) and input (supply-side filter).
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Power for the boost converter can come from any suitable DC source, such as batteries, solar panels, rectifiers, and DC generators.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] A process that changes one DC voltage to a different DC voltage is called DC-to-DC conversion.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] A boost converter is a DC-to-DC converter with an output voltage greater than the source voltage.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] A boost converter is sometimes called a step-up converter since it "steps up" the source voltage.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Since power ( ${\textstyle P=U\cdot I}$ ) must be conserved, the output current is lower than the source current.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The hydraulic ram can be seen as the hydraulic analogue to a boost converter.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] For high efficiency, the switched-mode power supply (SMPS) switch must turn on and off quickly and have low losses.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The advent of a commercial semiconductor switch in the 1950s represented a major milestone that made SMPSs such as the boost converter possible.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The major DC-to-DC converters were developed in the early 1960s when semiconductor switches had become available.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The aerospace industry’s need for small, lightweight, and efficient power converters led to the converter’s rapid development.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Switched systems such as SMPS are a challenge to design since their models depend on whether a switch is opened or closed.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Middlebrook from Caltech in 1977 published the models for DC-to-DC converters used today.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Middlebrook averaged the circuit configurations for each switch state in a technique called state-space averaging.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] This simplification reduced two systems into one.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The new model led to insightful design equations which helped the growth of SMPS.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Battery power systems often stack cells in series to achieve higher voltage.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] However, sufficient stacking of cells is not possible in many high voltage applications due to lack of space.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Boost converters can increase the voltage and reduce the number of cells.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Two battery-powered applications that use boost converters are used in hybrid electric vehicles (HEV) and lighting systems.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The NHW20 model Toyota Prius HEV uses a 500 V motor.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Without a boost converter, the Prius would need nearly 417 cells to power the motor.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] However, a Prius actually uses only 168 cells and boosts the battery voltage from 202 V to 500 V.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Boost converters also power devices at smaller scale applications, such as portable lighting systems.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] A white LED typically requires 3.3 V to emit light, and a boost converter can step up the voltage from a single 1.5 V alkaline cell to power the lamp.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] An unregulated boost converter is used as the voltage increase mechanism in the circuit known as the "Joule thief", based on blocking oscillator concepts.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] This circuit topology is used with low power battery applications, and is aimed at the ability of a boost converter to "steal" the remaining energy in a battery.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] This energy would otherwise be wasted since the low voltage of a nearly depleted battery makes it unusable for a normal load.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] This voltage decrease occurs as batteries become depleted, and is a characteristic of the ubiquitous alkaline battery.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Since the equation for power is ⁠ $\textstyle P={\frac {V^{2}}{R}}$ ⁠, and ⁠ R ⁠ tends to be stable, power available to the load goes down significantly as voltage decreases.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The special kind of boost-converters called voltage-lift type boost converters are used in solar photovoltaic (PV) systems.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] These power converters add up the passive components (diode, inductor and capacitor) of a traditional boost-converter to improve the power quality and increase the performance of complete PV system.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The key principle that drives the boost converter is the tendency of an inductor to resist changes in current by either increasing or decreasing the energy stored in the inductor's magnetic field.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] In a boost converter, the output voltage is always higher than the input voltage.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] A schematic of a boost power stage is shown in Figure 1.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] When the switch is closed ('on-state'), current flows through the inductor in the clockwise direction and the inductor stores some energy by generating a magnetic field.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The polarity of the left side of the inductor is positive.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] When the switch is opened ('off-state'), the magnetic field previously created will be reduced in energy to maintain the current through the inductor.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The polarity of the inductor will be reversed, which means the left side of the inductor will become negative.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] If the switch is cycled fast enough, the inductor will not discharge fully in between charging stages, and the load will always see a voltage greater than that of the input source alone when the switch is opened.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Also, while the switch is opened, the capacitor, in parallel with the load, is charged to this combined voltage.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] When the switch is then closed, and the right-hand side is shorted out from the left-hand side, the capacitor is, therefore, able to provide the voltage and energy to the load.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] During this time, the blocking diode prevents the capacitor from discharging through the switch.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The switch must, of course, be opened again fast enough to prevent the capacitor from discharging too much.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] This results in transferring the energy accumulated during the on-state into the capacitor.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The input current is the same as the inductor current, as shown in Figure 2.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] So, it is not discontinuous as in the buck converter, and the requirements on the input filter are relaxed compared to a buck converter.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] When a boost converter operates in continuous mode, the current through the inductor, ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {L} }$ ⁠, never falls to zero.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Figure 3 shows the typical waveforms of inductor current and voltage in a converter operating in this mode.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] In the steady state, the DC (average) voltage across the inductor must be zero so that after each cycle, the inductor returns the same state because the voltage across the inductor is proportional to the rate of change of current through it (explained in more detail below).
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Note in Figure 1 that the left-hand side of ⁠ L ⁠ is at ⁠ $V_{\mathrm {i} }$ ⁠, and the right-hand side of ⁠ L ⁠ sees the $V_{\mathrm {S} }$ voltage waveform from Figure 3.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The average value of $V_{\mathrm {S} }$ is ⁠ $(1-D)V_{\mathrm {o} }$ ⁠, where ⁠ D ⁠ is the duty cycle of the waveform driving the switch.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] It represents the fraction of the commutation period T during which the switch is on.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Therefore, D ranges between 0 (S is never on) and 1 (S is always on).
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] During the off-state, the switch S is open, so the inductor current flows through the load.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] As we consider that the converter operates in steady state conditions, the amount of energy stored in each of its components has to be the same at the beginning and at the end of a commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] So, the inductor current has to be the same at the start and end of the commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The above equation shows that the output voltage is always higher than the input voltage (as the duty cycle goes from 0 to 1), and that it increases with ⁠ D ⁠, theoretically to infinity as D approaches 1.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] This is why this converter is sometimes referred to as a 'step-up' converter.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] If the ripple amplitude of the current is too high, the inductor may be completely discharged before the end of a whole commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] In this case, the current through the inductor falls to zero during part of the period (see waveforms in Figure 4).
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Although the difference is slight, it has a strong effect on the output voltage equation.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The load current $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ is equal to the average diode current ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {D} }$ ⁠.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] As can be seen in Figure 4, the diode current is equal to the inductor current during the off-state.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] The average value of $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ can be sorted out geometrically from Figure 4.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Compared to the expression of the output voltage gain for continuous mode, this expression is much more complicated.
[src:buck-converter/boost-converter] Furthermore, in discontinuous operation, the output voltage gain not only depends on the duty cycle ⁠ D ⁠, but also on the inductor value ⁠ L ⁠, the input voltage ⁠ $V_{\mathrm {i} }$ ⁠, the commutation period ⁠ T ⁠, and the output current ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ ⁠.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The **buck–boost converter** is a type of DC-to-DC converter that has an output voltage magnitude that is either greater than or less than the input voltage magnitude.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] It is equivalent to a flyback converter using a single inductor instead of a transformer.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Two different topologies are called *buck–boost converter*.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Both of them can produce a range of output voltages, ranging from much larger (in absolute magnitude) than the input voltage, down to almost zero.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] In the inverting topology, the output voltage is of the opposite polarity than the input.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] This is a switched-mode power supply with a similar circuit configuration to the boost converter and the buck converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The output voltage is adjustable based on the duty cycle of the switching transistor.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] One possible drawback of this converter is that the switch does not have a terminal at ground; this complicates the driving circuitry.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] However, this drawback is of no consequence if the power supply is isolated from the load circuit (if, for example, the supply is a battery) because the supply and diode polarity can simply be reversed.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] When they can be reversed, the switch can be placed either on the ground side or the supply side.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] When a buck (step-down) converter is combined with a boost (step-up) converter, the output voltage is typically of the same polarity of the input, and can be lower or higher than the input.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Like the buck and boost converters, the operation of the buck–boost is best understood in terms of the inductor's "reluctance" to allow rapid change in current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] From the initial state in which nothing is charged and the switch is open, the current through the inductor is zero.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] When the switch is first closed, the blocking diode prevents current from flowing into the right hand side of the circuit, so it must all flow through the inductor.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] However, since the inductor doesn't allow rapid current change, it will initially keep the current low by opposing the voltage provided by the source.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Over time, the inductor will allow the current to slowly increase.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] In an ideal circuit the voltage across the inductor would remain constant, but when the inherent resistance of wiring, switch and the inductor itself is taken into account, the effective (electro-motive) voltage across the inductor will decrease as the current increases.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Also during this time, the inductor will store energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] If the current through the inductor L never falls to zero during a commutation cycle, the converter is said to operate in continuous mode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The current and voltage waveforms in an ideal converter can be seen in Figure 3.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] From *t* = 0 to *t* = *DT*, the converter is in on-state, so the switch S is closed.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Therefore D ranges between 0 (S is never on) and 1 (S is always on).
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] As we consider that the converter operates in steady-state conditions, the amount of energy stored in each of its components has to be the same at the beginning and at the end of a commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] From the above expression it can be seen that the polarity of the output voltage is always negative (because the duty cycle goes from 0 to 1), and that its absolute value increases with D, theoretically up to minus infinity when D approaches 1.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Apart from the polarity, this converter is either step-up (a boost converter) or step-down (a buck converter).
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Thus it is named a buck–boost converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] In some cases, the amount of energy required by the load is small enough to be transferred in a time smaller than the whole commutation period.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] In this case, the current through the inductor falls to zero during part of the period.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The only difference in the principle described above is that the inductor is completely discharged at the end of the commutation cycle (see waveforms in figure 4).
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Although slight, the difference has a strong effect on the output voltage equation.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The load current *I*o is equal to the average diode current *I*D.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] As can be seen on figure 4, the diode current is equal to the inductor current during the off-state.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Compared to the expression of the output voltage gain for the continuous mode, this expression is much more complicated.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Furthermore, in discontinuous operation, the output voltage not only depends on the duty cycle, but also on the inductor value, the input voltage and the output current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] As told at the beginning of this section, the converter operates in discontinuous mode when low current is drawn by the load, and in continuous mode at higher load current levels.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] As *I*o,lim is the current at the limit between continuous and discontinuous modes of operations, it satisfies the expressions of both modes.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] These expressions have been plotted in figure 5.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The difference in behavior between the continuous and discontinuous modes can be seen clearly.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The four-switch converter combines the buck and boost converters.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] It can operate in either the buck or the boost mode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] In either mode, only one switch controls the duty cycle, another is for commutation and must be operated inversely to the former one, and the remaining two switches are in a fixed position.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] A two-switch buck–boost converter can be built with two diodes, but upgrading the diodes to FET switches doesn't cost much extra while efficiency improves due to the lower voltage drop.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] In the analysis above, no dissipative elements (resistors) have been considered.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] That means that the power is transmitted without losses from the input voltage source to the load.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] However, parasitic resistances exist in all circuits, due to the resistivity of the materials they are made from.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Therefore, a fraction of the power managed by the converter is dissipated by these parasitic resistances.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] For the sake of simplicity, we consider here that the inductor is the only non-ideal component, and that it is equivalent to an inductor and a resistor in series.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] This assumption is acceptable because an inductor is made of one long wound piece of wire, so it is likely to exhibit a non-negligible parasitic resistance *R*L.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Furthermore, current flows through the inductor both in the on and the off states.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] where ${\bar {V_{\mathrm {L} }}}$ and ${\bar {V_{\mathrm {S} }}}$ are respectively the average voltage across the inductor and the switch over the commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] If we consider that the converter operates in steady-state, the average current through the inductor is constant.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] When the switch is in the on-state, *V*S = 0.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The output current is the opposite of the inductor current during the off-state.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] The average inductor current is therefore: ${\bar {I_{\mathrm {L} }}}={\frac {-I_{\mathrm {o} }}{1-D}}.$ Assuming the output current and voltage have negligible ripple, the load of the converter can be considered purely resistive.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] If the inductor resistance is zero, the equation above becomes equal to that of the *ideal* case.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] But when *R*L increases, the voltage gain of the converter decreases compared to the ideal case.
[src:buck-converter/buck-boost-converter] Furthermore, the influence of *R*L increases with the duty cycle.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A **buck converter** or **step-down converter** is a DC-to-DC converter which decreases voltage, while increasing current, from its input (*supply*) to its output (*load*).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] It is a class of switched-mode power supply.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Switching converters (such as buck converters) provide much greater power efficiency as DC-to-DC converters than linear regulators, which are simpler circuits that dissipate power as heat, but do not step up output current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The efficiency of buck converters can be very high, often over 90%, making them useful for tasks such as converting a computer's main supply voltage, which is usually 12 V, down to lower voltages needed by USB, DRAM and the CPU, which are usually 5, 3.3 or 1.8 V.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] To reduce voltage ripple, filters made of capacitors (sometimes in combination with additional inductors) are normally added to such a converter's output (load-side filter) and input (supply-side filter).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Its name derives from the inductor that “bucks” or opposes the supply voltage.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Buck converters typically operate with a switching frequency range from 100 kHz to a few MHz.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A higher switching frequency allows for use of smaller inductors and capacitors, but also increases lost efficiency to more frequent transistor switching.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Disconnect the source and use the inertia of the current in the inductor to provide more current than the source delivers ("off" in fig.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] To close the circuit with the source disconnected, a second switch, usually a diode, is needed.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] During on-state, the source may need to momentarily provide more current than its rating for constant load allows, but the on-time is too short for the source to take damage.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] During off-state, no current is drawn from the source, and the components can cool down.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The average current draw over both states needs to be below the source specification.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] To even out voltage spikes from the switching between on-state and off-state, a capacitor is used on the output side.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A mechanical analogy for a buck converter would be to pedal a bicycle in single, strong bursts (force ~ voltage), and let the bicycle roll in between (inertia ~ inductor).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The basic operation of the buck converter has the current in an inductor controlled by two switches (fig.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In a physical implementation, these switches are realized by a transistor and a diode, or two transistors (which avoids the loss associated with the diode's voltage drop).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The conceptual model of the buck converter is best understood in terms of the relation between current and voltage of the inductor.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Beginning with the switch open (off-state), the current in the circuit is zero.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] When the switch is first closed (on-state), the current will begin to increase, and the inductor will produce an opposing voltage across its terminals in response to the changing current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This voltage drop counteracts the voltage of the source and therefore reduces the net voltage across the load.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Over time, the rate of change of current decreases, and the voltage across the inductor also then decreases, increasing the voltage at the load.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] During this time, the inductor stores energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] If the switch is opened while the current is still changing, then there will always be a voltage drop across the inductor, so the net voltage at the load will always be less than the input voltage source.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] When the switch is opened again (off-state), the voltage source will be removed from the circuit, and the current will decrease.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The decreasing current will produce a voltage drop across the inductor (opposite to the drop at on-state), and now the inductor becomes a current source.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The stored energy in the inductor's magnetic field supports the current flow through the load.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This current, flowing while the input voltage source is disconnected, when appended to the current flowing during on-state, totals to current greater than the average input current (being zero during off-state).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The increase in average current makes up for the reduction in voltage, and ideally preserves the power provided to the load.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] During the off-state, the inductor is discharging its stored energy into the rest of the circuit.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] If the switch is closed again before the inductor fully discharges (on-state), the voltage at the load will always be greater than zero.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Buck converters operate in continuous mode if the current through the inductor ( $I_{\text{L}}$ ) never falls to zero during the commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Therefore, it can be seen that the energy stored in L increases during on-time as $I_{\text{L}}$ increases and then decreases during the off-state.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] L is used to transfer energy from the input to the output of the converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] where D is a scalar called the duty cycle with a value between 0 and 1.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Assuming that the converter operates in the steady state, the energy stored in each component at the end of a commutation cycle T is equal to that at the beginning of the cycle.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] That means that the current $I_{\text{L}}$ is the same at $t=0$ and at $t=T$ (figure 4).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The above integrations can be done graphically.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In figure 4, $\Delta I_{L_{\text{on}}}$ is proportional to the area of the yellow surface, and $\Delta I_{L_{\text{off}}}$ to the area of the orange surface, as these surfaces are defined by the inductor voltage (red lines).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] As these surfaces are simple rectangles, their areas can be found easily: $\left(V_{\text{i}}-V_{\text{o}}\right)t_{\text{on}}$ for the yellow rectangle and $-V_{\text{o}}t_{\text{off}}$ for the orange one.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] For steady state operation, these areas must be equal.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] From this equation, it can be seen that the output voltage of the converter varies linearly with the duty cycle for a given input voltage.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] As the duty cycle D is equal to the ratio between $t_{\text{on}}$ and the period T , it cannot be more than 1.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This is why this converter is referred to as *step-down converter*.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] So, for example, stepping 12 V down to 3 V (output voltage equal to one quarter of the input voltage) would require a duty cycle of 25%, in this theoretically ideal circuit.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In some cases, the amount of energy required by the load is too small.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The only difference in the principle described above is that the inductor is completely discharged at the end of the commutation cycle (see figure 5).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This has, however, some effect on the previous equations.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The inductor current falling below zero results in the discharging of the output capacitor during each cycle and therefore higher switching losses.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A different control technique known as pulse-frequency modulation can be used to minimize these losses.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] We still consider that the converter operates in steady state.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Therefore, the energy in the inductor is the same at the beginning and at the end of the cycle (in the case of discontinuous mode, it is zero).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This means that the average value of the inductor voltage (VL) is zero; i.e., that the area of the yellow and orange rectangles in figure 5 are the same.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The output current delivered to the load ( $I_{\text{o}}$ ) is constant, as we consider that the output capacitor is large enough to maintain a constant voltage across its terminals during a commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This implies that the current flowing through the capacitor has a zero average value.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Where ${\overline {I_{\text{L}}}}$ is the average value of the inductor current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] As can be seen in figure 5, the inductor current waveform has a triangular shape.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The inductor current is zero at the beginning and rises during ton up to ILmax.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] It can be seen that the output voltage of a buck converter operating in discontinuous mode is much more complicated than its counterpart of the continuous mode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Furthermore, the output voltage is now a function not only of the input voltage (Vi) and the duty cycle D, but also of the inductor value (L), the commutation period (T) and the output current (Io).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The converter operates in discontinuous mode when low current is drawn by the load, and in continuous mode at higher load current levels.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The limit between discontinuous and continuous modes is reached when the inductor current falls to zero exactly at the end of the commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] On the limit between the two modes, the output voltage obeys both the expressions given respectively in the continuous and the discontinuous sections.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] These expressions have been plotted in figure 6.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] From this, it can be deduced that in continuous mode, the output voltage does only depend on the duty cycle, whereas it is far more complex in the discontinuous mode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This is important from a control point of view.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] These assumptions can be fairly far from reality, and the imperfections of the real components can have a detrimental effect on the operation of the converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Output voltage ripple is the name given to the phenomenon where the output voltage rises during the On-state and falls during the Off-state.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Several factors contribute to this including, but not limited to, switching frequency, output capacitance, inductor, load and any current limiting features of the control circuitry.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] We can best approximate output ripple voltage by shifting the output current versus time waveform (continuous mode) down so that the average output current is along the time axis.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] When we do this, we see the AC current waveform flowing into and out of the output capacitor (sawtooth waveform).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] We note that *V*c-min (where *V*c is the capacitor voltage) occurs at *t*on/2 (just after capacitor has discharged) and *V*c-max at *t*off/2.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A full explanation is given there.) We note from basic AC circuit theory that our ripple voltage should be roughly sinusoidal: capacitor impedance times ripple current peak-to-peak value, or Δ*V* = Δ*I* / (ω*C*) where ω = 2π*f*, *f* is the ripple frequency, and *f* = 1/*T*, *T* the ripple period.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This gives: Δ*V* = Δ*I* *T*/2π*C*), and we compare to this value to confirm the above in that we have a factor of 8 vs a factor of ~ 6.3 from basic AC circuit theory for a sinusoid.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This gives confidence in our assessment here of ripple voltage.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The paragraph directly below pertains that directly above and may be incorrect.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Once again, please see talk tab for more: pertaining output ripple voltage and AoE (Art of Electronics 3rd edition).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] During the off-state, the current in this equation is the load current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In the on-state the current is the difference between the switch current (or source current) and the load current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The duration of time (d*T*) is defined by the duty cycle and by the switching frequency.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Qualitatively, as the output capacitance or switching frequency increase, the magnitude of the ripple decreases.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Output voltage ripple is typically a design specification for the power supply and is selected based on several factors.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Capacitor selection is normally determined based on cost, physical size and non-idealities of various capacitor types.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Switching frequency selection is typically determined based on efficiency requirements, which tends to decrease at higher operating frequencies, as described below in Effects of non-ideality on the efficiency.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Higher switching frequency can also raise EMI concerns.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Output voltage ripple is one of the disadvantages of a switching power supply, and can also be a measure of its quality.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The simplified analysis above, does not account for non-idealities of the circuit components nor does it account for the required control circuitry.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Power losses due to the control circuitry are usually insignificant when compared with the losses in the power devices (switches, diodes, inductors, etc.) The non-idealities of the power devices account for the bulk of the power losses in the converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Both static and dynamic power losses occur in any switching regulator.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Static power losses include $I^{2}R$ (conduction) losses in the wires or PCB traces, as well as in the switches and inductor, as in any electrical circuit.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Dynamic power losses occur as a result of switching, such as the charging and discharging of the switch gate, and are proportional to the switching frequency.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The voltage drops described above are all static power losses which are dependent primarily on DC current, and can therefore be easily calculated.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] For a diode drop, *V*sw and *V*sw,sync may already be known, based on the properties of the selected device.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The duty cycle equation is somewhat recursive.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A rough analysis can be made by first calculating the values *V*sw and *V*sw,sync using the ideal duty cycle equation.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] For a MOSFET voltage drop, a common approximation is to use RDSon from the MOSFET's datasheet in Ohm's law, V = IDSRDSon(sat).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This approximation is acceptable because the MOSFET is in the linear state, with a relatively constant drain-source resistance.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This approximation is only valid at relatively low VDS values.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] For more accurate calculations, MOSFET datasheets contain graphs on the VDS and IDS relationship at multiple VGS values.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Observe VDS at the VGS and IDS which most closely match what is expected in the buck converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In addition, power loss occurs as a result of leakage currents.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Dynamic power losses are due to the switching behavior of the selected pass devices (MOSFETs, power transistors, IGBTs, etc.).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] These losses include turn-on and turn-off switching losses and switch transition losses.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] but this does not take into account the parasitic capacitance of the MOSFET which makes the *Miller plate*.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] When a MOSFET is used for the lower switch, additional losses may occur during the time between the turn-off of the high-side switch and the turn-on of the low-side switch, when the body diode of the low-side MOSFET conducts the output current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This time, known as the non-overlap time, prevents "shoot-through", a condition in which both switches are simultaneously turned on.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The onset of shoot-through generates severe power loss and heat.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Proper selection of non-overlap time must balance the risk of shoot-through with the increased power loss caused by conduction of the body diode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Many MOSFET based buck converters also include a diode to aid the lower MOSFET body diode with conduction during the non-overlap time.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] When a diode is used exclusively for the lower switch, diode forward turn-on time can reduce efficiency and lead to voltage overshoot.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Finally, power losses occur as a result of the power required to turn the switches on and off.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] For MOSFET switches, these losses are dominated by the energy required to charge and discharge the capacitance of the MOSFET gate between the threshold voltage and the selected gate voltage.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] These switch transition losses occur primarily in the gate driver, and can be minimized by selecting MOSFETs with low gate charge, by driving the MOSFET gate to a lower voltage (at the cost of increased MOSFET conduction losses), or by operating at a lower frequency.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] For N-MOSFETs, the high-side switch must be driven to a higher voltage than *Vi*.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] To achieve this, MOSFET gate drivers typically feed the MOSFET output voltage back into the gate driver.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The gate driver then adds its own supply voltage to the MOSFET output voltage when driving the high-side MOSFETs to achieve a *VGS* equal to the gate driver supply voltage.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Because the low-side *VGS* is the gate driver supply voltage, this results in very similar *VGS* values for high-side and low-side MOSFETs.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A complete design for a buck converter includes a tradeoff analysis of the various power losses.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Designers balance these losses according to the expected uses of the finished design.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A converter expected to have a low switching frequency does not require switches with low gate transition losses; a converter operating at a high duty cycle requires a low-side switch with low conduction losses.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A synchronous buck converter is a modified version of the basic buck converter circuit topology in which the diode, D, is replaced by a second switch, S2.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This modification is a tradeoff between increased cost and improved efficiency.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In a standard buck converter, the flyback diode turns on, on its own, shortly after the switch turns off, as a result of the rising voltage across the diode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] By replacing the diode with a switch selected for low loss, the converter efficiency can be improved.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In both cases, power loss is strongly dependent on the duty cycle, D.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Power loss on the freewheeling diode or lower switch will be proportional to its on-time.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Therefore, systems designed for low duty cycle operation will suffer from higher losses in the freewheeling diode or lower switch, and for such systems it is advantageous to consider a synchronous buck converter design.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Consider a computer power supply, where the input is 5 V, the output is 3.3 V, and the load current is 10 A.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In this case, the duty cycle will be 66% and the diode would be on for 34% of the time.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A typical diode with forward voltage of 0.7 V would suffer a power loss of 2.38 W.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A well-selected MOSFET with RDSon of 0.015 Ω, however, would waste only 0.51 W in conduction loss.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This translates to improved efficiency and reduced heat generation.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Another advantage of the synchronous converter is that it is bi-directional, which lends itself to applications requiring regenerative braking.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] When power is transferred in the "reverse" direction, it acts much like a boost converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The advantages of the synchronous buck converter do not come without cost.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] First, the lower switch typically costs more than the freewheeling diode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Second, the complexity of the converter is vastly increased due to the need for a complementary-output switch driver.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Such a driver must prevent both switches from being turned on at the same time, a fault known as "shootthrough".
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The simplest technique for avoiding shootthrough is a time delay between the turn-off of S1 to the turn-on of S2, and vice versa.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] However, setting this time delay long enough to ensure that S1 and S2 are never both on will itself result in excess power loss.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] An improved technique for preventing this condition is known as adaptive "non-overlap" protection, in which the voltage at the switch node (the point where S1, S2 and L are joined) is sensed to determine its state.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] When the switch node voltage passes a preset threshold, the time delay is started.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The driver can thus adjust to many types of switches without the excessive power loss this flexibility would cause with a fixed non-overlap time.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Both low side and high side switches may be turned off in response to a load transient and the body diode in the low side MOSFET or another diode in parallel with it becomes active.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The higher voltage drop on the low side switch is then of benefit, helping to reduce current output and meet the new load requirement sooner.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The multiphase buck converter is a circuit topology where basic buck converter circuits are placed in parallel between the input and load.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Each of the *n* "phases" is turned on at equally spaced intervals over the switching period.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This circuit is typically used with the synchronous buck topology, described above.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This type of converter can respond to load changes as quickly as if it switched *n* times faster, without the increase in switching losses that would cause.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Thus, it can respond to rapidly changing loads, such as modern microprocessors.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] There is also a significant decrease in switching ripple.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Another advantage is that the load current is split among the *n* phases of the multiphase converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This load splitting allows the heat losses on each of the switches to be spread across a larger area.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This circuit topology is used in computer motherboards to convert the 12 VDC power supply to a lower voltage (around 1 V), suitable for the CPU.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Modern CPU power requirements can exceed 200 W, can change very rapidly, and have very tight ripple requirements, less than 10 mV.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Typical CPU power supplies found on mainstream motherboards use 3 or 4 phases, while high-end systems can have 16 or more phases.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] One major challenge inherent in the multiphase converter is ensuring the load current is balanced evenly across the *n* phases.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This current balancing can be performed in a number of ways.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Current can be measured "losslessly" by sensing the voltage across the inductor or the lower switch (when it is turned on).
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This technique is considered lossless because it relies on resistive losses inherent in the buck converter topology.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Another technique is to insert a small resistor in the circuit and measure the voltage across it.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This approach is more accurate and adjustable, but incurs several costs—space, efficiency and money.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Finally, the current can be measured at the input.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Voltage can be measured losslessly, across the upper switch, or using a power resistor, to approximate the current being drawn.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This approach is technically more challenging, since switching noise cannot be easily filtered out.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] However, it is less expensive than having a sense resistor for each phase.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] There are two main phenomena impacting the efficiency: conduction losses and switching losses.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Conduction losses happen when current is flowing through the components and thus depend on the load.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] They are caused by Joule effect in the resistance when the transistor or MOSFET switch is conducting, the inductor winding resistance, and the capacitor equivalent series resistance.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Losses are proportional to the square of the current in this case.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Conduction losses are also generated by the diode forward voltage drop (usually 0.7 V or 0.4 V for Schottky diode), and are proportional to the current in this case.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] Switching losses happen in the transistor and diode when the voltage and the current overlap during the transitions between closed and open states.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A Schottky diode can be used to minimize the switching losses caused by the reverse recovery of a regular PN diode.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] The switching losses are proportional to the switching frequency.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] In a complete real-world buck converter, there is also a command circuit to regulate the output voltage or the inductor current.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This circuit and the MOSFET gate controller have a power consumption, impacting the overall efficiency of the converter.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] A buck converter can be used to maximize the power transfer through the use of impedance matching.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] An application of this is in a *maximum power point tracker* commonly used in photovoltaic systems.
[src:buck-converter/buck-converter] This is particularly useful in applications where the impedances are dynamically changing.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The **Ćuk converter** (Serbo-Croatian: [tɕûːk], English: /ˈtʃuːk/) is a type of buck-boost converter with low ripple current.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] A Ćuk converter can be seen as a combination of boost converter and buck converter, having one switching device and a mutual capacitor, to couple the energy.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Similar to the buck-boost converter with inverting topology, the output voltage of non-isolated Ćuk converter is typically inverted, with lower or higher values with respect to the input voltage.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] While DC-to-DC converters usually use the inductor as a main energy-storage component, the Ćuk converter instead uses the capacitor as the main energy-storage component.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] It is named after Slobodan Ćuk of the California Institute of Technology, who first presented the design.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] There are variations on the basic Ćuk converter.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] For example, the coils may share a single magnetic core, which drops the output ripple, and adds efficiency.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Because the power transfer flows continuously via the capacitor, this type of switcher has minimized EMI radiation.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The Ćuk converter allows energy to flow bidirectionally by using a diode and a switch.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] A non-isolated Ćuk converter comprises two inductors, two capacitors, a switch (usually a transistor), and a diode.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] It is an inverting converter, so the output voltage is negative with respect to the input voltage.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The main **advantage** of this converter is the continuous currents at the input and output of the converter.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The main **disadvantage** is the high current stress on the switch, as it carries the sum of the input current and the output current.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The capacitor C1 is used to transfer energy.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] It is connected alternately to the input and to the output of the converter *via* the commutation of the transistor and the diode (see figures 2 and 3).
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The two inductors L1 and L2 are used to convert respectively the input voltage source (*Vs*) and the output voltage (*Vo*) into current sources.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] At a short time scale, an inductor can be considered as a current source as it maintains a constant current.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] This conversion is necessary because if the capacitor were connected directly to the voltage source, the current would be limited only by the parasitic resistance, resulting in high energy loss.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Charging a capacitor with a current source (the inductor) prevents resistive current limiting and its associated energy loss.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] As with other converters (buck converter, boost converter, buck–boost converter) the Ćuk converter can operate in either continuous or discontinuous current mode.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] However, unlike these converters, it can also operate in *discontinuous voltage mode* (the voltage across the capacitor drops to zero during the commutation cycle).
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] In steady state, the energy stored in each inductor has to remain the same at the beginning and at the end of a commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] This implies that the current through each inductor has to be the same at the beginning and the end of the commutation cycle.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] it can be seen that the average value of each inductor's voltage over a commutation period has to be zero to satisfy the steady-state requirements.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The converter operates in *on state* from ${\textstyle t=0}$ to ${\textstyle t=DT}$ (*D* is the duty cycle), and in *off state* from *D·T* to *T* (that is, during a period equal to ${\textstyle (1-D)T}$ ).
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] It can be seen that this relation is the same as that obtained for the buck–boost converter.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Like all DC/DC converters, Ćuk converters rely on the ability of the inductors in the circuit to provide continuous current, in much the same way a capacitor in a rectifier filter provides continuous voltage.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] If this inductor is too small or below the "critical inductance", then the inductor current slope will be discontinuous where the current goes to zero.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] This state of operation is usually not studied in much depth as it is generally not used beyond a demonstrating of why the minimum inductance is crucial, although it may occur when maintaining a standby voltage at a much lower current than the converter was designed for.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Where $f_{s}$ is the switching frequency.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Coupled inductor isolated Ćuk converter.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] For isolated version of Ćuk converter, an AC transformer and an additional capacitor must be added.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Because the isolated Ćuk converter is isolated, the output-voltage polarity can be chosen freely.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] As the non-isolated Ćuk converter, the isolated Ćuk converter can have an output voltage magnitude that is either greater than or less than the input voltage magnitude, even with a 1:1 AC transformer.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] However, the turns ratio can be controlled to reduce device stress on the input side.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Additionally, the parasitic elements of the transformer, namely leakage inductance and magnetizing inductance can be used to modify the circuit into a resonant converter circuit which has much improved efficiency.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Instead of using two discrete inductor components, many designers implement a *coupled inductor Ćuk converter*, using a single magnetic component that includes both inductors on the same core.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The transformer action between the inductors inside that component gives a *coupled inductor Ćuk converter* with lower output ripple than a Ćuk converter using two independent discrete inductor components.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] A zeta converter is a non-isolated, non-inverting, buck-boost power supply topology.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] Unlike the Ćuk and SEPIC converters, which are configured with a standard boost converter consisting of a series inductor and parallel switch, a zeta converter is configured with a buck converter constructed from a series switch and parallel inductor.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The zeta converter typically uses a high-side PFET for the series switch, in contrast to the typical implementation of a low-side NFET in Ćuk and SEPIC converters.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The zeta converter topology benefits from lower output voltage ripple and easier compensation than SEPIC converters.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] The tradeoff is higher input voltage ripple, the need for a large capacitor, and a specialised controller capable of driving a PFET.
[src:buck-converter/ćuk-converter] A SEPIC is a non-isolated, non-inverting DC-to-DC converter topology, it is similar to the Ćuk converter, but has the output inductor and diode swapped in position and the output capacitor flipped if it is polarized, it also has the same relation of input and output voltage.
